<div id="review_2512731613" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2512731613" />
    <a title="Atikah Wahid" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9139351-atikah-wahid"><img alt="Atikah Wahid" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1488377032p2/9139351.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2512731613?book_show_action=true">Aug 30, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Atikah Wahid" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Atikah Wahid" href="/user/show/9139351-atikah-wahid">Atikah Wahid</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9139351-atikah-wahid?shelf=did-not-finish">did-not-finish</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9139351-atikah-wahid?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9139351-atikah-wahid?shelf=anthology">anthology</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2512731613" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6668288967833386849">One star because I didn&apos;t finish it. <br/><br/>I have always wanted to read this book as I&apos;ve heard many praises for this book and author. Yasmin has been helmed as a very influential and enlightening speaker. So, when my mum brought home a signed copy, I thought it was a great opportunity to learn of her ideas and thoughts about life that is also from an Islamic perspective. I&apos;m no stranger to self-help books. I like self-help books that are more on the practical side, the ones that actually show us step</span>
  <span id="freeText6668288967833386849" style="display:none">One star because I didn't finish it. <br /><br />I have always wanted to read this book as I've heard many praises for this book and author. Yasmin has been helmed as a very influential and enlightening speaker. So, when my mum brought home a signed copy, I thought it was a great opportunity to learn of her ideas and thoughts about life that is also from an Islamic perspective. I'm no stranger to self-help books. I like self-help books that are more on the practical side, the ones that actually show us steps to self-development rather than just pretty purple prose. I'm not against purple prose but I do need the content to be backed up by some meatier content. Unfortunately, that is not this book. This is pretty much purple prose from cover to cover. <br /><br />This book's message could easily be summarised to this sentence: Loving <i>dunya</i>, or the material world, is a mistake because it is temporary while loving God is fulfilling as God is The Almighty who created the world and is infinite. I'm sure Yasmin had written a much better sentence than that ten times over throughout this book but you get the picture. That message could easily be written on a bookmark. Yasmin has written a book with a message that is very repetitive and does not go deeper than that one sentence. It is also not very original since many Islamic speakers touch on this very message. Sure, she helpfully provides Quranic verses to support her writing but don't go looking for a deeper analysis than that. <br /><br />One of my issues about this book is her call for detachment of the world, including people. In fact, that topic is in the first chapter. I'm sorry but my family and friends are usually one of the few people who would help me during tough times so why should I be detached from them? And aren't having loving and supportive people in your life God's blessing in itself? Also, undermining material wealth seems like a privileged position - imagine telling a homeless person that money is meaningless. Somebody who would have a stable economical standing in life would be far suited to aim for enlightenment than someone who live day to day in peril. For someone who has asked us to leave the worldly matters behind, she keeps talking about it but does not provide any means to "detach" ourselves from <i>dunya</i>. Being alive on Earth, this <i>dunya</i>, could be years, decades even. So, how does one deal with living in this temporary plane while only focusing on the <i>akhirah</i>? Shouldn't we aim for a balance of both? Furthermore, call me a cynic, but I find it ironic that Yasmin asks us to detach ourselves from material wealth when her book has a "Bestseller" sticker on it.<br /><br />Looking at the ratings of this book and the clear popularity of it, there is an audience for this book. I think people who are already in touch with their spiritual and religious side would find benefit from this. After all, a lot of self-help books are simply platforms to tell us what we already know but needed that extra affirmation. The short chapters of this book will also help for those who want quick daily life affirmations. But if you're just slightly on the cynical side like me, Yasmin's rather vague but poetic writing will leave you wanting. Apparently, this book is actually a compilation of her online articles. I recognised a few of the articles on her blog but also, the other articles on her website are so much better because they are much more personal. In the book, Yasmin would steer clear from anything too specific - she would state in an article that she was in a distressing period of her life and would leave it at that - which makes me feel rather detached from her writing. But in her blog, she actually touches on personal issues like her struggle with depression during high school, which I found more interesting and relateable. However, I suppose, since the article did not end with any religious message, it was not included. To be honest, I would be more interested to learn how she overcame or continues to overcome her depression from an Islamic perspective rather than a collection of vague positive affirmations. Reading this book, I just could not relate to her writing at all. So, I highly recommend reading her blog instead. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6668288967833386849" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


