<div id="review_1279485254" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1279485254" />
    <a title="Sahar" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11180459-sahar"><img alt="Sahar" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1618432028p2/11180459.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1279485254?book_show_action=true">May 23, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sahar" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sahar" href="/user/show/11180459-sahar">Sahar</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11180459-sahar?shelf=islam">islam</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11180459-sahar?shelf=spirituality">spirituality</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1279485254" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2377930378558902017">I am absolutely infatuated with this book. It is a profound and inspirational gem and I’m so glad I read it. The book almost functions as a self-reflective journal, firstly outlining the inevitable difficulties of life and then grounding these struggles in light of Islam and what the religion teaches. It is full of beautifully insightful anecdotes and eye-opening reminders. The one thing I truly adored about this work was Mogahed’s unrelenting centring of every situation in light of God and what</span>
  <span id="freeText2377930378558902017" style="display:none">I am absolutely infatuated with this book. It is a profound and inspirational gem and I’m so glad I read it. The book almost functions as a self-reflective journal, firstly outlining the inevitable difficulties of life and then grounding these struggles in light of Islam and what the religion teaches. It is full of beautifully insightful anecdotes and eye-opening reminders. The one thing I truly adored about this work was Mogahed’s unrelenting centring of every situation in light of God and what God wants from us. Her love and adoration of the Divine was literally <i>pouring</i> off the pages. She was also very spot-on in articulating the musings of lay Muslims. Her inner reflections were peppered throughout with Qur’anic verses and ahadith to support her arguments, making it an addictive and uplifting read. <br /><br />I feel like this is a book that, no matter how many times one reads, there will ALWAYS be a new reminder or lesson. Yasmin Mogahed is an incredibly articulate and sound writer. I found this book extremely beneficial and If I could rate this book 10 stars, I would. <br /><br /><i> My body came from the ground and it will go back to the ground, as it came. It was only a shell, a container for my soul. A companion for a while. But I’ll leave it here when I arrive. Arrive—not depart. Because that’s my home. Not this. That’s why when Allah (swt) is calling the back the righteous soul, He says, ‘irjiee’: return. (Qur’an, 89:28)</i><br /><br />(side note I met Yasmin Mogahed in 2016 at an event and she is such a radiant person inside and out subhaAllah)</span>
  <a data-text-id="2377930378558902017" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

