<div id="review_2031775397" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2031775397" />
    <a title="Yazlina Saduri" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9764348-yazlina-saduri"><img alt="Yazlina Saduri" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1496927674p2/9764348.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2031775397?book_show_action=true">Jun 16, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Yazlina Saduri" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Yazlina Saduri" href="/user/show/9764348-yazlina-saduri">Yazlina Saduri</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2031775397" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12307749160217574621">The writer in my opinion explains brilliantly, simple questions which normally entail complicated answers. I personally boil within these hurting questions; why do they (Mom &amp; Dad) leave me too soon? It&apos;s so not fair. Others I know are in their 50s and still have their Mom or / Dad to embrace. I was merely in my 20s when they were taken. Why? I must be way too heavy with sins that Allah hates me enough to take Mom and Dad too soon. I should continue to grief and feel bad right? All these dissati</span>
  <span id="freeText12307749160217574621" style="display:none">The writer in my opinion explains brilliantly, simple questions which normally entail complicated answers. I personally boil within these hurting questions; why do they (Mom &amp; Dad) leave me too soon? It's so not fair. Others I know are in their 50s and still have their Mom or / Dad to embrace. I was merely in my 20s when they were taken. Why? I must be way too heavy with sins that Allah hates me enough to take Mom and Dad too soon. I should continue to grief and feel bad right? All these dissatisfaction should push me to the ignorance corner already right? If given a chance, I will leave everything and have my parents back. Yasmin explained why I should not. I must not become "captive inside my own desires".<br /><br />Yasmin used many amazing metaphors to further explain her statements. One of many I like so much is that about the vase.... "the problem wasn't the vase, or even that the vases kept breaking. The problem was that I kept putting them on the edge of tables. .... where it will inevitably fall...".<br /><br />I think many of us find it easier to give up 'asking for something" from God through 'dua'... we ask and ask and the answers or help we look for never come. "We are always looking for signs. We are always asking for God to 'speak' to us. But those signs are all around us. They are in everything. God is always 'speaking'. The question is whether we are listening."<br /><br />This book is a must read and I am grateful for Allah's arrangement that I read it. Alhamdulillah.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12307749160217574621" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


