<span id="freeTextContainer846613418931416684">hmmm... Ibn Ata Allah meets Dr. Phil* ? :-)<br/><br/>I highly recommend this book, especially for anyone who hasn&apos;t read any books under the more traditional &quot;Islamic Spirituality&quot; classification. Yasmin does a great job of hammering in some important points (that if we truly internalized, we&apos;d be a lot less bent out of shape about a lot of things) using very simple prose.<br/><br/>You can find most of the chapters on her blog (<a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='http://www.yasminmogahed.com'>http://www.yasminmogahed.com</a>) so feel free to take a look there for a preview. <br/><br/>-1 star f</span>
  <span id="freeText846613418931416684" style="display:none">hmmm... Ibn Ata Allah meets Dr. Phil* ? :-)<br /><br />I highly recommend this book, especially for anyone who hasn't read any books under the more traditional "Islamic Spirituality" classification. Yasmin does a great job of hammering in some important points (that if we truly internalized, we'd be a lot less bent out of shape about a lot of things) using very simple prose.<br /><br />You can find most of the chapters on her blog (<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.yasminmogahed.com">http://www.yasminmogahed.com</a>) so feel free to take a look there for a preview. <br /><br />-1 star for some repetitiveness and I'm not a fan of poetry (don't judge me) while the book's final chapter is all poems.<br /><br /><br />* I've never read a Dr. Phil book so I'm just assuming here </span>
