  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2832506428" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2832506428" />
    <a title="Aurélien Thomas" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19341029-aur-lien-thomas"><img alt="Aurélien Thomas" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1568508113p2/19341029.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2832506428?book_show_action=true">May 24, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aurélien Thomas" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aurélien Thomas" href="/user/show/19341029-aur-lien-thomas">Aurélien Thomas</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780990387688" href="/book/show/26314701-reclaim-your-heart">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19341029-aur-lien-thomas?shelf=islam">islam</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2832506428" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11324998992913989709"><i>&apos;The tragedy of our choice is that we chain our necks with attachements, and then ask why we choke… But what we have done, we have done to ourselves.&apos;<br/><br/>&apos;We all have needs and we all have wants. Our true suffering begins when we turn our wants into needs.&apos;</i><br/><br/>Have I been a Muslim, or a believer for that matter, I would have put a five star. I am not, and so I will have to point at its flaws despite agreeing with, in essence, the core of her message: life is not about being happy. Life is about being at</span>
  <span id="freeText11324998992913989709" style="display:none"><i>'The tragedy of our choice is that we chain our necks with attachements, and then ask why we choke… But what we have done, we have done to ourselves.'<br /><br />'We all have needs and we all have wants. Our true suffering begins when we turn our wants into needs.'</i><br /><br />Have I been a Muslim, or a believer for that matter, I would have put a five star. I am not, and so I will have to point at its flaws despite agreeing with, in essence, the core of her message: life is not about being happy. Life is about being at peace. <br /><br />Let's start with what we have in common. Happiness indeed is a fleeting feeling, dependent on many factors that are everything but stable, immanent, permanent. Relationships, career, money, fame and other worldly rewards might make you happy for a while, but as they come and go, and are everything but reliable and satisfactory (there's always more to get, and more to get, and more to get, all the while fearing to loose part or all of what you already have!) that you would be unwise to make them the centre of your life's purpose. For the author indeed, chasing happiness can only put you through a roller coaster; and the ride will have the exact opposite effect of what you are striving for: it won't make you happy, but unsatisfied and craving for more, if not afraid of loosing what you have. I agree with that! So forget about chasing happiness, and instead strive to be at peace. And I agree with that too! <br /><br />Ah! But where do you find peace? Well, that's where me and her diverge.<br /><br />Since what is temporary and unreliable cannot be counted upon to fulfil us, only what is eternal, never change and is always there to be trusted can do so. What's that? To her: God. And, not only that, but as a Muslim she then details a precise relationship with God which is very deep and enlightening (e.g. the way she explains the relevance of the Five Pillars of Islam are a case in point...). With beautiful and clever metaphors, that all make the point straightforwardly, here are a series of short chapters away from dry metaphysics, pompous dogma and silly and easy self-help book that are so fashion nowadays! I love the beauty of her thinking, the clarity of her reasoning, and so I understand how it can appeal to believers. Actually, if you are one, READ THIS BOOK! It will be comforting, and surely will put your faith into a new perspective. Thing is... <br /><br />Thing is, I am an atheist; and so I have to point at her flaws, or rather prejudices and misunderstandings. <br /><br />Can peace only be found by relying on God? I don't know how familiar she is, if at all, with Stoicism, Buddhism, or even Taoism. Yet such philosophies are claiming exactly what she does (peace vs happiness) BUT with a crucial difference: peace comes from within, certainly not an outside deity. Plus, they have a lot to teach about 'attachement' that, I am sure, many agreeing with her will find relevant, if not echoing some of their preoccupations. Does it matter? Well, that's a crucial point because not grasping it leads her to two blunders. <br /><br />First, she assumes that not having any sense of a grander spiritual purpose can only throw you down hedonism and materialism:<br /><br /><i>'if one believes that this life is the Reality, the final destination, the goal of all endeavours, the purpose of life would be to maximize pleasure and gain.'</i><br /><br />It's not true. One doesn't need a God to have a strong moral compass, like one doesn't need a Deity to be empathetic, loving, selfless and nurturing. <br /><br />Then, because she assumes that not believing in life after death is a gloomy and pessimistic view:<br /><br /><i>'Imagine a world where you have to fall, bleed and eventually die was the only paradise you knew. Imagine the agony of that.'</i><br /><br />Again: it's not true. If anything, not clinging to the wishful thinking that might be a life after death (better that this one, of course, why not have your cake and eat it!) makes this life even more precious to cherish and be grateful for. There is no agony; just an humbling experience.<br /><br />Having said that, here's a wonderful book, both very intelligent and truly poetic (she actually use poetry as well to get her point across). It will be very useful to believers (Muslims in particular) so as to put their faith into a new perspective. It will be very relevant and enlightening too to others, in helping them understand how believing in God can be fulfilling. I surely was annoyed by her prejudices towards an atheistic worldview, but that aside I found it all very profound without being preachy. After all, our mindsets may wander different paths; but our hearts are on the same journey: own life, and not be owned by it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11324998992913989709" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

